INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In the context of Software-Defined Networking (SDN) and Cisco DNA Center, what is the primary architectural difference between an SDN model and a traditional network model regarding the control plane?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"In SDN, every network device independently runs its own routing protocol; in traditional networking, a central controller makes all forwarding decisions."},{"id":"b","text":"In SDN, a centralized controller programs the data plane of devices; in traditional networking, each device runs a distributed control plane."},{"id":"c","text":"In SDN, the data plane and control plane are co-located on every device; in traditional networking, they are separated."},{"id":"d","text":"In SDN, only the southbound API is used to communicate with external applications; in traditional networking, only northbound APIs exist."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Traditional: distributed control plane (each device runs routing). SDN: centralized control plane (controller programs data plane).' This is the defining architectural distinction. Option A reverses the definitions. Option C incorrectly describes traditional networking — in traditional networks, the control and data plane are integrated per device, but SDN separates them by centralizing the control plane. Option D incorrectly describes API directions: northbound APIs face applications/orchestration, and southbound APIs face network devices, in both traditional and SDN contexts.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/software-defined-networking/overview.html","label":"Cisco Software-Defined Networking Overview"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/cloud-systems-management/dna-center/nb-06-dna-center-arch-design-guide-cte-en.html","label":"Cisco DNA Center Architecture and Design Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In the context of Software-Defined Networking (SDN) and Cisco DNA Center, what is the primary architectural difference between an SDN model and a traditional network model regarding the control plane?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer needs to collect high-frequency streaming telemetry data from Cisco IOS-XE devices using a model-driven, push-based approach. Which protocol is best suited for this use case?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"NETCONF with get-config RPC"},{"id":"b","text":"SNMP polling over UDP"},{"id":"c","text":"gNMI over gRPC"},{"id":"d","text":"RESTCONF with HTTP GET"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes 'gNMI/gRPC: model-driven telemetry, high-frequency push.' gNMI (gRPC Network Management Interface) is specifically designed for streaming, push-based, high-frequency telemetry using gRPC as its transport. NETCONF get-config is a pull-based operation for configuration retrieval. SNMP polling is a legacy pull mechanism not suited for high-frequency streaming. RESTCONF with HTTP GET is also a pull-based request-response model, not a streaming telemetry solution.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/prog/configuration/1612/b_1612_programmability_cg/model_driven_telemetry.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE Model-Driven Telemetry Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://github.com/openconfig/gnmi/blob/master/proto/gnmi/gnmi.proto","label":"gNMI Specification – OpenConfig"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer needs to collect high-frequency streaming telemetry data from Cisco IOS-XE devices using a model-driven, push-based approach. Which protocol is best suited for this use case?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator wants to automate a response to a specific syslog event directly on a Cisco IOS router without relying on any external controller or script host. Which Cisco on-device automation feature should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cisco DNA Center Intent API"},{"id":"b","text":"Ansible ios_config module"},{"id":"c","text":"NETCONF edit-config RPC"},{"id":"d","text":"Cisco Embedded Event Manager (EEM)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cisco EEM (Embedded Event Manager): on-device automation via applets and Tcl scripts.' EEM runs directly on the IOS device and can trigger actions in response to events such as syslog messages, without any external controller or management host. Cisco DNA Center Intent API is an external northbound REST API requiring an external controller. Ansible ios_config is an external agentless tool that still requires a control node outside the device. NETCONF edit-config is a protocol used by external management systems to push configuration — it does not provide on-device event-driven automation.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/eem/configuration/xe-16/eem-xe-16-book/eem-overview.html","label":"Cisco Embedded Event Manager (EEM) Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/ios-xe/eem/","label":"Cisco DevNet – EEM Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator wants to automate a response to a specific syslog event directly on a Cisco IOS router without relying on any external controller or script host. Which Cisco on-device automation feature should be used?$patch$);

-- 200-301-P2: 40 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is troubleshooting a connectivity issue and needs to identify which OSI layer is responsible for routing packets based on a destination IP address. Which layer handles this function?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Layer 1 – Physical"},{"id":"b","text":"Layer 2 – Data Link"},{"id":"c","text":"Layer 3 – Network"},{"id":"d","text":"Layer 4 – Transport"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Layer 3: router (routes packets based on dst IP).' The Network layer (Layer 3) of the OSI model is responsible for logical addressing and routing. Routers operate at this layer and make forwarding decisions based on destination IP addresses. Layer 2 (Data Link) forwards frames based on MAC addresses, Layer 1 (Physical) handles raw bit transmission, and Layer 4 (Transport) handles end-to-end communication (e.g., TCP/UDP).$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/training-events/training-certifications/certifications/associate/ccna.html","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – OSI Model"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/article/osi-model-reference-chart","label":"Cisco Learning Network – OSI Layers"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is troubleshooting a connectivity issue and needs to identify which OSI layer is responsible for routing packets based on a destination IP address. Which layer handles this function?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which IPv4 address range is defined by RFC 1918 as a private address space that is NOT routable on the public internet?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"169.254.0.0/16"},{"id":"b","text":"172.16.0.0/12"},{"id":"c","text":"127.0.0.0/8"},{"id":"d","text":"224.0.0.0/4"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly lists RFC 1918 private ranges as: '10/8, 172.16-31/12, 192.168/16.' The 172.16.0.0/12 block (172.16.0.0–172.31.255.255) is one of the three private ranges. The 169.254.0.0/16 range is APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing), assigned when DHCP fails — not an RFC 1918 private range. The 127.0.0.0/8 range is the loopback range. The 224.0.0.0/4 range is reserved for IPv4 multicast.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc1918","label":"RFC 1918 – Address Allocation for Private Internets"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/13772-12.html","label":"Cisco – Private IP Addressing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which IPv4 address range is defined by RFC 1918 as a private address space that is NOT routable on the public internet?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch receives a frame destined for a MAC address that does not exist in its MAC address table. What action will the switch take?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Drop the frame and send an ICMP Destination Unreachable message to the sender."},{"id":"b","text":"Forward the frame only to the default gateway port."},{"id":"c","text":"Flood the frame out all ports except the port on which it was received."},{"id":"d","text":"Buffer the frame and wait for an ARP reply to resolve the destination MAC address."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Flooding (unknown unicast/multicast/broadcast)' is the switch behavior for unknown destinations. When a switch has no entry for the destination MAC in its CAM (MAC address table), it treats the frame as an unknown unicast and floods it out all ports except the ingress port. This is distinct from filtering (where a frame is dropped) and forwarding (where a frame is sent to a known port). Switches do not generate ICMP messages or interact with ARP; those are Layer 3/Layer 2 address-resolution mechanisms handled by end-hosts and routers.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/ethernet/10023-3.html","label":"Cisco – How Switches Work (CAM Table and Flooding)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/training-events/training-certifications/certifications/associate/ccna.html","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – Ethernet Switching"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch receives a frame destined for a MAC address that does not exist in its MAC address table. What action will the switch take?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer needs to provide a point-to-point serial link between two routers and wants to conserve IPv4 address space with the smallest possible subnet. Which subnet mask should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"/28 — provides 14 usable host addresses"},{"id":"b","text":"/30 — provides 2 usable host addresses"},{"id":"c","text":"/29 — provides 6 usable host addresses"},{"id":"d","text":"/27 — provides 30 usable host addresses"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: '/30 = 4 addrs (2 usable, point-to-point).' A /30 subnet has 4 total addresses (network, two hosts, broadcast), making it the conventional choice for a point-to-point link requiring exactly two host addresses. It conserves address space far better than /29 (6 usable), /28 (14 usable), or /27 (30 usable). Note: RFC 3021 /31 masks can also be used for point-to-point links without a broadcast address, but /30 is the traditional and most commonly tested answer for this scenario in the CCNA exam context.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3021","label":"RFC 3021 – Using 31-Bit Prefixes on IPv4 Point-to-Point Links"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – IP Addressing and Subnetting for New Users"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer needs to provide a point-to-point serial link between two routers and wants to conserve IPv4 address space with the smallest possible subnet. Which subnet mask should be used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which IPv6 address type is automatically assigned to every IPv6-enabled interface and is only valid for communication on the local network segment?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Global Unicast address (2000::/3)"},{"id":"b","text":"Unique Local address (FC00::/7)"},{"id":"c","text":"Link-Local address (FE80::/10)"},{"id":"d","text":"Multicast address (FF00::/8)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies 'Link-Local (FE80::/10)' as one of the IPv6 address types. Link-Local addresses are automatically generated on every IPv6 interface (typically using EUI-64 or a random identifier) and are confined to the local network segment — they are not routable beyond a single link. Global Unicast addresses (2000::/3) are globally routable like public IPv4 addresses. Unique Local addresses (FC00::/7) are similar to RFC 1918 private IPv4 addresses but are routable within an organization. Multicast addresses (FF00::/8) are used to send traffic to multiple recipients simultaneously.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipv6_basic/configuration/xe-16/ip6b-xe-16-book/ip6-add-basic-conn.html","label":"Cisco – IPv6 Addressing Overview"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc4291","label":"RFC 4291 – IP Version 6 Addressing Architecture"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which IPv6 address type is automatically assigned to every IPv6-enabled interface and is only valid for communication on the local network segment?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Cisco switch is being configured from scratch. After connecting via console, the engineer types 'enable' at the prompt. Which IOS mode is the engineer now in?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"User EXEC mode, indicated by the '>' prompt"},{"id":"b","text":"Global Configuration mode, indicated by '(config)#'"},{"id":"c","text":"Privileged EXEC mode, indicated by the '#' prompt"},{"id":"d","text":"Interface Configuration mode, indicated by '(config-if)#'"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes Cisco IOS modes as: 'User EXEC (>), Privileged EXEC (#), Global config, Interface config modes.' Typing 'enable' from User EXEC mode (>) elevates the session to Privileged EXEC mode, which is identified by the '#' prompt. This mode allows access to all monitoring commands and is the gateway to Global Configuration mode (entered via 'configure terminal'). The engineer cannot directly reach Global Configuration or Interface Configuration modes without first entering Privileged EXEC mode.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/fundamentals/command/cf_command_ref/enable.html","label":"Cisco IOS Configuration Fundamentals Command Reference – CLI Modes"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/article/cisco-routers-and-ios-basics","label":"Cisco Learning Network – IOS CLI Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Cisco switch is being configured from scratch. After connecting via console, the engineer types 'enable' at the prompt. Which IOS mode is the engineer now in?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which network device operates exclusively at OSI Layer 1 and forwards all received signals out every other port without any awareness of MAC addresses or IP addresses?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Layer 2 switch"},{"id":"b","text":"Hub"},{"id":"c","text":"Multilayer switch"},{"id":"d","text":"Router"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Layer 1: hub, repeater (broadcast, no MAC awareness).' A hub is a Layer 1 device that simply regenerates and broadcasts received electrical signals out all other ports. It has no ability to inspect MAC or IP addresses, so all devices connected to a hub share a single collision domain. In contrast, a Layer 2 switch uses a MAC address table to make intelligent forwarding decisions (reducing collisions), a multilayer switch adds Layer 3 routing capabilities, and a router operates at Layer 3 using IP addresses.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/enterprise-networks/what-is-a-network-switch.html","label":"Cisco – Network Topologies and Devices"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/training-events/training-certifications/certifications/associate/ccna.html","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – Ethernet and Switching"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which network device operates exclusively at OSI Layer 1 and forwards all received signals out every other port without any awareness of MAC addresses or IP addresses?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An IPv6 host uses EUI-64 to automatically generate its interface ID. What is the source material used by EUI-64 to construct the 64-bit host portion of the IPv6 address?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The host's IPv4 address, padded with zeros to 64 bits"},{"id":"b","text":"A randomly generated 64-bit value assigned by the DHCPv6 server"},{"id":"c","text":"The interface's 48-bit MAC address, modified by inserting FF:FE in the middle and flipping the U/L bit"},{"id":"d","text":"The router's Global Unicast prefix concatenated with the host's loopback address"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'EUI-64 builds host portion from MAC.' The EUI-64 process takes the interface's 48-bit MAC address, splits it in half, inserts the hex value FF:FE between the two halves to create a 64-bit value, and then flips the 7th bit (the Universal/Local bit) to indicate that the address is locally unique. For example, a MAC of AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF becomes AA:BB:CC:FF:FE:DD:EE:FF, with the U/L bit modified. This method does not use the host's IPv4 address, DHCPv6, or the router's prefix for the host-ID portion.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/ip-version-6-ipv6/113361-ipv6-eui64-00.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding IPv6 EUI-64 Bit Address"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc4291#section-2.5.1","label":"RFC 4291 – IPv6 Addressing Architecture (EUI-64)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An IPv6 host uses EUI-64 to automatically generate its interface ID. What is the source material used by EUI-64 to construct the 64-bit host portion of the IPv6 address?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to carry traffic for VLANs 10, 20, and 30 across an uplink between two Cisco switches. Which port type and tagging standard should be configured on the uplink interfaces?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Access port using ISL tagging"},{"id":"b","text":"Trunk port using 802.1Q tagging"},{"id":"c","text":"Access port using 802.1Q tagging"},{"id":"d","text":"Trunk port using 802.3ad tagging"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that trunk ports carry multiple VLANs using 802.1Q tagging. Access ports carry only a single VLAN and traffic is untagged. ISL is a legacy Cisco proprietary encapsulation no longer supported on modern Cisco switches, and 802.3ad is the standard for EtherChannel link aggregation, not VLAN tagging. 802.1Q is the correct and current standard for VLAN tagging on trunk links.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_vtp.html","label":"Cisco – VLAN Configuration Guide, 802.1Q Trunking"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9780138229306","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – VLANs and Trunking"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to carry traffic for VLANs 10, 20, and 30 across an uplink between two Cisco switches. Which port type and tagging standard should be configured on the uplink interfaces?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$What is the size of an 802.1Q VLAN tag inserted into an Ethernet frame, and which field value identifies it as an 802.1Q tag?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"2 bytes; identified by TPID value 0x8100"},{"id":"b","text":"4 bytes; identified by TPID value 0x8100"},{"id":"c","text":"4 bytes; identified by TPID value 0x0800"},{"id":"d","text":"8 bytes; identified by TPID value 0x8100"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: '802.1Q tag is 4 bytes (TPID 0x8100 + TCI with PCP/DEI/VID 12-bit).' The Tag Protocol Identifier (TPID) value 0x8100 marks the frame as carrying an 802.1Q tag. 0x0800 is the EtherType for IPv4, not for 802.1Q. The tag is not 2 or 8 bytes.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://standards.ieee.org/ieee/802.1Q/6844/","label":"IEEE 802.1Q-2018 Standard – VLAN Tagging"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/17056-741-4.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding 802.1Q VLAN Encapsulation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$What is the size of an 802.1Q VLAN tag inserted into an Ethernet frame, and which field value identifies it as an 802.1Q tag?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security-conscious administrator wants to prevent Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP) from automatically negotiating trunk links on end-user access ports. Which command should be applied to those ports?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"switchport mode dynamic auto"},{"id":"b","text":"switchport mode dynamic desirable"},{"id":"c","text":"switchport mode access"},{"id":"d","text":"switchport nonegotiate"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'DTP: Dynamic Trunking Protocol (auto/desirable); for security use "switchport mode access" or "trunk".' Configuring 'switchport mode access' explicitly sets the port to access mode and disables DTP negotiation. 'dynamic auto' and 'dynamic desirable' both participate in DTP negotiation. While 'switchport nonegotiate' also disables DTP, the source material specifically calls out 'switchport mode access' as the security best practice for end-user ports.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/10558-17.html","label":"Cisco – Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP) Overview"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9780138229306","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – VLANs and Trunking"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security-conscious administrator wants to prevent Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP) from automatically negotiating trunk links on end-user access ports. Which command should be applied to those ports?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is implementing inter-VLAN routing on a single router connected to a Layer 2 switch carrying multiple VLANs. The engineer creates logical subinterfaces on the router's physical interface. Which configuration approach does this describe?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Switch Virtual Interface (SVI) routing"},{"id":"b","text":"Router-on-a-stick using subinterfaces with dot1q encapsulation"},{"id":"c","text":"Layer 3 EtherChannel inter-VLAN routing"},{"id":"d","text":"Bridged virtual interface (BVI) routing"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Router-on-a-stick: subinterfaces with encapsulation dot1q.' This design uses a single physical router interface divided into logical subinterfaces, each assigned a VLAN and configured with 'encapsulation dot1q <vlan-id>'. SVIs are a Layer 3 switch feature and do not use subinterfaces on a router. EtherChannel is a link-aggregation technology. BVI is used in bridge-group configurations, not standard inter-VLAN routing.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/inter-vlan-routing/41860-howto-L3-intervlanrouting.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Router-on-a-Stick Inter-VLAN Routing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is implementing inter-VLAN routing on a single router connected to a Layer 2 switch carrying multiple VLANs. The engineer creates logical subinterfaces on the router's physical interface. Which configuration approach does this describe?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In a network running Rapid PVST+ (802.1w), which three port states are used compared to the five states in classic 802.1D STP?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Blocking, listening, forwarding"},{"id":"b","text":"Discarding, learning, forwarding"},{"id":"c","text":"Blocking, learning, forwarding"},{"id":"d","text":"Discarding, listening, forwarding"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material clearly differentiates: 'Port states (STP): blocking, listening, learning, forwarding, disabled. RSTP: discarding, learning, forwarding.' RSTP consolidates the blocking, listening, and disabled states of 802.1D into a single 'discarding' state, resulting in three states: discarding, learning, and forwarding. Options A, C, and D incorrectly mix states from 802.1D with RSTP or use non-existent combinations.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/24062-146.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1w)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
