INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer wants to bundle four Gigabit Ethernet links between two Cisco switches using an open-standard protocol that supports negotiation. Which EtherChannel protocol and mode combination is the correct choice?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"PAgP with desirable/desirable mode"},{"id":"b","text":"LACP with active/passive mode"},{"id":"c","text":"PAgP with auto/auto mode"},{"id":"d","text":"LACP with on/on mode"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'LACP (open standard, 802.3ad), PAgP (Cisco proprietary). Modes: LACP active/passive, PAgP desirable/auto, on (no negotiation).' LACP is the open IEEE 802.3ad standard, making it the correct choice when an open standard is required. Configuring one side as active and the other as passive (or both active) allows LACP negotiation. PAgP is Cisco proprietary. 'on/on' mode uses no negotiation protocol at all, which does not satisfy the negotiation requirement.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/link_agg/b_179_link_agg_9300_cg/configuring_etherchannel.html","label":"Cisco – EtherChannel Configuration Guide (LACP and PAgP)"},{"url":"https://standards.ieee.org/ieee/802.3ad/1049/","label":"IEEE 802.3ad Link Aggregation Standard"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer wants to bundle four Gigabit Ethernet links between two Cisco switches using an open-standard protocol that supports negotiation. Which EtherChannel protocol and mode combination is the correct choice?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless deployment uses multiple lightweight access points that tunnel both control and data traffic to a central controller. Which protocol facilitates this tunneling between the APs and the controller?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"LWAPP (Lightweight Access Point Protocol)"},{"id":"b","text":"CAPWAP (Control and Provisioning of Wireless Access Points)"},{"id":"c","text":"GRE (Generic Routing Encapsulation)"},{"id":"d","text":"MPLS (Multiprotocol Label Switching)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Lightweight APs use CAPWAP tunnel to WLC (control + data).' CAPWAP is the standard protocol used to establish control and data tunnels between lightweight APs and a Wireless LAN Controller (WLC). LWAPP was a predecessor to CAPWAP and is no longer used in current Cisco deployments. GRE is a generic tunneling protocol not specific to wireless architectures. MPLS is a routing/forwarding technology unrelated to AP-to-controller communication.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless/aironet-1600-series/116493-technote-ap-00.html","label":"Cisco – CAPWAP and Lightweight AP Overview"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5415","label":"RFC 5415 – CAPWAP Protocol Specification"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
