INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During an NTP configuration review, a junior engineer notes that a core router is configured with the command 'ntp master 3'. The router has no reachable external NTP source. What does this command cause the router to do?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The router refuses to serve NTP to any client until an external stratum 3 source is found."},{"id":"b","text":"The router acts as an NTP server at stratum 3 using its own internal clock, even without an external time source."},{"id":"c","text":"The router synchronizes only with peers that advertise stratum 3 or lower."},{"id":"d","text":"The router sends NTP authentication challenges to all clients using MD5 at stratum 3."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly notes 'NTP master to act as server without external sync.' The 'ntp master [stratum]' command makes the router an authoritative NTP source at the specified stratum level, using its internal hardware clock. This allows downstream devices to synchronize even when no upstream reference is available. Option A is incorrect because the router does not refuse to serve time; it serves from its internal clock. Option C misinterprets 'master' as a filtering mechanism. Option D confuses the master command with NTP authentication (MD5), which is a separate feature.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/bsm/configuration/xe-16/bsm-xe-16-book/bsm-time-calendar-set.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring NTP (IOS)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During an NTP configuration review, a junior engineer notes that a core router is configured with the command 'ntp master 3'. The router has no reachable external NTP source. What does this command cause the router to do?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A host inside a corporate network with the private IP address 10.10.10.50 sends traffic to the internet. The NAT router translates this address to the public IP 203.0.113.10. In Cisco NAT terminology, what is 10.10.10.50 called?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Inside global"},{"id":"b","text":"Outside local"},{"id":"c","text":"Inside local"},{"id":"d","text":"Outside global"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines 'Inside local (private inside)' as the private IP address of a host located on the inside network — exactly what 10.10.10.50 is before translation. 'Inside global' (option A) is the public IP address that represents the inside host to the outside world (203.0.113.10 in this scenario). 'Outside local' (option B) is how an outside host's address appears to the inside network. 'Outside global' (option D) is the actual public IP address of an outside host. Understanding these four NAT address terms is fundamental to NAT troubleshooting.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/4606-8.html","label":"Cisco - NAT: Local and Global Definitions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A host inside a corporate network with the private IP address 10.10.10.50 sends traffic to the internet. The NAT router translates this address to the public IP 203.0.113.10. In Cisco NAT terminology, what is 10.10.10.50 called?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network operations team wants to ensure that voice traffic across their enterprise WAN receives the lowest possible delay and jitter. According to QoS best practices, which DSCP value and queuing mechanism combination is most appropriate for voice bearer (RTP) traffic?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DSCP AF41 with Class-Based Weighted Fair Queueing (CBWFQ)"},{"id":"b","text":"DSCP EF (46) with Low Latency Queueing (LLQ)"},{"id":"c","text":"DSCP CS3 with Weighted Random Early Detection (WRED)"},{"id":"d","text":"DSCP Default (0) with Priority Queueing (PQ)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states 'EF (Expedited Forwarding, DSCP 46) for voice' and 'LLQ (Low Latency Queueing) for voice.' EF provides a consistent, low-delay forwarding treatment, and LLQ adds a strict-priority queue ensuring voice packets are serviced before all other traffic, minimizing delay and jitter. AF41 with CBWFQ (option A) is suitable for video conferencing but does not guarantee the strict priority treatment voice requires. CS3 with WRED (option C) is used for call-signaling traffic, not bearer. DSCP Default with PQ (option D) provides no QoS differentiation for voice.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/qos_classn/configuration/xe-16/qos-classn-xe-16-book/qos-classn-mrkg-qos-grp.html","label":"Cisco - QoS for Voice over IP"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/quality-of-service-qos/qos-packet-marking/10103-dscpvalues.html","label":"Cisco - Low Latency Queueing (LLQ) Design Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network operations team wants to ensure that voice traffic across their enterprise WAN receives the lowest possible delay and jitter. According to QoS best practices, which DSCP value and queuing mechanism combination is most appropriate for voice bearer (RTP) traffic?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security-conscious organization needs their network management system (NMS) to receive notifications from Cisco routers whenever a critical event occurs, and they require confirmation that each notification was actually received by the NMS. Which SNMP mechanism satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"SNMP Get"},{"id":"b","text":"SNMP Trap"},{"id":"c","text":"SNMP Inform"},{"id":"d","text":"SNMP Set"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material distinguishes 'trap (notification)' from 'inform (acked notification).' An SNMP Inform is identical to a Trap in that the agent pushes an unsolicited notification to the NMS, but critically, the NMS sends an acknowledgment back to the agent. If no acknowledgment is received, the agent retransmits the Inform, guaranteeing delivery. A Trap (option B) is fire-and-forget with no acknowledgment and can be silently lost. SNMP Get (option A) is a polling operation initiated by the NMS to read values. SNMP Set (option D) is used by the NMS to modify values on the agent — neither is a notification mechanism.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/snmp/configuration/xe-16/snmp-xe-16-book/nm-snmp-cfg-snmp-support.html","label":"Cisco - Configuring SNMP Support"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security-conscious organization needs their network management system (NMS) to receive notifications from Cisco routers whenever a critical event occurs, and they require confirmation that each notification was actually received by the NMS. Which SNMP mechanism satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator wants to permit traffic only from the 192.168.10.0/24 network to reach a specific server and deny all other traffic. Which type of ACL and placement strategy should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Standard ACL applied closest to the source"},{"id":"b","text":"Extended ACL applied closest to the source"},{"id":"c","text":"Standard ACL applied closest to the destination"},{"id":"d","text":"Extended ACL applied closest to the destination"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Standard ACLs (numbered 1-99 or 1300-1999) match only on source IP address. Because they cannot specify a destination, placing them closest to the destination ensures traffic from other sources is not inadvertently blocked before it can reach other resources. As the source material states: 'Standard ACLs … match source IP only; apply closest to destination.' Extended ACLs match both source and destination and should be placed closest to the source. Option B is wrong because extended ACLs are needed for src/dst specificity. Options A and D are mismatched type-to-placement combinations.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html","label":"Cisco – ACL Overview and Guidelines"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator wants to permit traffic only from the 192.168.10.0/24 network to reach a specific server and deny all other traffic. Which type of ACL and placement strategy should be used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An extended ACL has the following entries in order: (1) permit tcp 10.1.1.0 0.0.0.255 any eq 80, (2) deny ip 10.1.1.50 0.0.0.0 any, (3) permit ip any any. A packet from host 10.1.1.50 destined for port 80 is evaluated. What happens to this packet?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The packet is denied by entry 2"},{"id":"b","text":"The packet is permitted by entry 1"},{"id":"c","text":"The packet is permitted by entry 3"},{"id":"d","text":"The packet is dropped by the implicit deny"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$ACLs are processed top-down with first-match logic. Entry 1 permits TCP from the entire 10.1.1.0/24 network (which includes 10.1.1.50) destined to any address on port 80. Because this packet matches entry 1 first, it is permitted immediately. Entry 2 is never reached. The source material states: 'Order matters (top-down, first match).' Options A, C, and D are incorrect because processing stops at the first matching entry — entry 1 in this case.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html","label":"Cisco – How ACLs Work"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An extended ACL has the following entries in order: (1) permit tcp 10.1.1.0 0.0.0.255 any eq 80, (2) deny ip 10.1.1.50 0.0.0.0 any, (3) permit ip any any. A packet from host 10.1.1.50 destined for port 80 is evaluated. What happens to this packet?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch port is configured with port security using the 'sticky' option and the violation mode set to 'restrict'. What occurs when an unauthorized MAC address is detected on that port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The port is immediately placed into an err-disabled state and must be manually re-enabled"},{"id":"b","text":"Frames from the unauthorized MAC address are dropped and a violation counter is incremented, but the port remains up"},{"id":"c","text":"Frames from the unauthorized MAC address are silently discarded with no log or counter increment"},{"id":"d","text":"The unauthorized MAC address is dynamically added to the secure MAC table and traffic is forwarded"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Port security offers three violation modes: shutdown (err-disables the port — option A), restrict (drops frames from offending MACs and increments the violation counter while keeping the port active — the correct answer), and protect (silently drops frames with no counter increment — option C). Option D describes normal sticky learning, which only occurs for MACs that fall within the allowed maximum before a violation event. The source material lists 'shutdown/restrict/protect violation modes' as distinct behaviors.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst2960x/software/15-2_7_e/configuration_guide/b_1527e_consolidated_2960x_cg/configuring_port_security.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Port Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch port is configured with port security using the 'sticky' option and the violation mode set to 'restrict'. What occurs when an unauthorized MAC address is detected on that port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$DHCP snooping has been enabled on a Cisco switch. Which type of message does DHCP snooping drop when received on an untrusted port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DHCP Discover messages from client hosts"},{"id":"b","text":"DHCP Request messages from client hosts"},{"id":"c","text":"DHCP Offer and DHCP Acknowledge messages from DHCP servers"},{"id":"d","text":"DHCP Release messages from client hosts"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$DHCP snooping distinguishes between trusted ports (connected to legitimate DHCP servers or uplinks) and untrusted ports (connected to end hosts). As the source material states: 'Drops bogus DHCP server responses (offer/ack) on untrusted [ports].' Client-originated messages such as Discover, Request, and Release are permitted on untrusted ports because legitimate clients generate them. Options A, B, and D describe client-side messages which are allowed through untrusted ports.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/sec/b_179_sec_9300_cg/configuring_dhcp_snooping.html","label":"Cisco – DHCP Snooping Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
