INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is reviewing the OSI model. Which layer is responsible for routing packets based on destination IP addresses?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Layer 1 – Physical"},{"id":"b","text":"Layer 2 – Data Link"},{"id":"c","text":"Layer 3 – Network"},{"id":"d","text":"Layer 4 – Transport"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Layer 3: router (routes packets based on dst IP).' The Network layer (Layer 3) of the OSI model handles logical addressing and path determination using IP addresses. Layer 2 (Data Link) uses MAC addresses for local delivery, Layer 4 (Transport) manages end-to-end communication (TCP/UDP), and Layer 1 (Physical) deals only with raw bit transmission.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/routers/12000-series-routers/47321-ciscoios-hints-12000.html","label":"Cisco – OSI Model Overview"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco Learning Network – CCNA 200-301 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is reviewing the OSI model. Which layer is responsible for routing packets based on destination IP addresses?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A host has been assigned the IP address 172.20.5.10/12. According to RFC 1918, which private address range does this address belong to?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"10.0.0.0/8"},{"id":"b","text":"172.16.0.0/12"},{"id":"c","text":"192.168.0.0/16"},{"id":"d","text":"169.254.0.0/16"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists the RFC 1918 private ranges as: '10/8, 172.16-31/12, 192.168/16.' The address 172.20.5.10 falls within 172.16.0.0 through 172.31.255.255, which is the 172.16.0.0/12 private block. 10.0.0.0/8 covers addresses starting with 10. 192.168.0.0/16 covers addresses starting with 192.168. 169.254.0.0/16 is the APIPA range, used when a host cannot obtain a DHCP address — it is not an RFC 1918 private range.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc1918","label":"RFC 1918 – Address Allocation for Private Internets"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding IP Addressing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A host has been assigned the IP address 172.20.5.10/12. According to RFC 1918, which private address range does this address belong to?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch receives a frame destined for a MAC address that does not exist in its MAC address table. What action will the switch take?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Drop the frame immediately."},{"id":"b","text":"Send the frame only to the default gateway."},{"id":"c","text":"Flood the frame out all ports except the port on which it was received."},{"id":"d","text":"Forward the frame only to the port associated with the source MAC address."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Flooding (unknown unicast/multicast/broadcast), filtering (drop), forwarding.' When a switch does not have an entry in its MAC address table (CAM table) for the destination MAC address, it floods the frame out all ports except the ingress port — this is called unknown unicast flooding. Dropping the frame is the filtering action applied to frames that should not be forwarded. Forwarding only to the source port or the default gateway are incorrect behaviors.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/switches/catalyst-6500-series-switches/23563-143.html","label":"Cisco – Catalyst Switch MAC Address Table and Unicast Flooding"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco Learning Network – CCNA 200-301 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch receives a frame destined for a MAC address that does not exist in its MAC address table. What action will the switch take?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An IPv6 address begins with FE80::1. Which type of IPv6 address is this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Global Unicast"},{"id":"b","text":"Unique Local"},{"id":"c","text":"Multicast"},{"id":"d","text":"Link-Local"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material specifies IPv6 address types including 'Link-Local (FE80::/10).' An address beginning with FE80 falls within the FE80::/10 prefix and is a link-local address, valid only on the local network segment. Global Unicast addresses begin with 2000::/3. Unique Local addresses use the FC00::/7 prefix. Multicast addresses use FF00::/8. Link-local addresses are automatically configured on every IPv6-enabled interface and are not routable beyond the local link.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipv6_basic/configuration/xe-16/ip6b-xe-16-book/ip6-add-basic-conn.html","label":"Cisco – IPv6 Addressing and Basic Connectivity"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc4291","label":"RFC 4291 – IP Version 6 Addressing Architecture"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An IPv6 address begins with FE80::1. Which type of IPv6 address is this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to connect two routers using a point-to-point serial link and wants to conserve IP address space. Which subnet mask provides exactly two usable host addresses while eliminating the need for a broadcast address as defined in RFC 3021?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"/28 (255.255.255.240)"},{"id":"b","text":"/30 (255.255.255.252)"},{"id":"c","text":"/31 (255.255.255.254)"},{"id":"d","text":"/32 (255.255.255.255)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: '/31 (RFC 3021) for p2p without broadcast.' A /31 subnet contains exactly two addresses, both of which are usable as host addresses, because RFC 3021 eliminates the requirement for a dedicated network and broadcast address on point-to-point links. A /30 provides four addresses with two usable, but still includes a network and broadcast address. A /28 provides 14 usable addresses — far more than needed. A /32 is a host route assigned to a single interface (e.g., loopback) with no room for a second host.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3021","label":"RFC 3021 – Using 31-Bit Prefixes on IPv4 Point-to-Point Links"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – IP Addressing Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to connect two routers using a point-to-point serial link and wants to conserve IP address space. Which subnet mask provides exactly two usable host addresses while eliminating the need for a broadcast address as defined in RFC 3021?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician is cabling a new office that requires 10 Gbps Ethernet over copper for a distance of 95 meters. Which cable category should be selected to reliably meet both the speed and distance requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cat5e"},{"id":"b","text":"Cat6"},{"id":"c","text":"Cat6a"},{"id":"d","text":"Single-mode fiber"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cat5e (1 Gbps, 100m), Cat6 (1-10 Gbps), Cat6a (10 Gbps, 100m).' Cat6a is the correct answer because it is rated for 10 Gbps at distances up to 100 meters, comfortably covering 95 meters. Cat5e supports only 1 Gbps. Cat6 can support 10 Gbps but only at reduced distances (typically up to 55 meters), making it unreliable at 95 meters for 10 Gbps. Single-mode fiber is a valid technology for long-distance 10 Gbps but is not a copper cabling solution, which the scenario implies.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/switches/catalyst-9300-series-switches/guide-c07-742051.html","label":"Cisco – Cabling Guide for Cisco Catalyst Switches"},{"url":"https://www.tiaonline.org/standard/tia-568/","label":"TIA-568 Cabling Standard (ANSI/TIA)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician is cabling a new office that requires 10 Gbps Ethernet over copper for a distance of 95 meters. Which cable category should be selected to reliably meet both the speed and distance requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Cisco IOS command mode allows an administrator to make global configuration changes that affect the entire router, such as setting the hostname?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"User EXEC mode (Router>)"},{"id":"b","text":"Privileged EXEC mode (Router#)"},{"id":"c","text":"Global Configuration mode (Router(config)#)"},{"id":"d","text":"Interface Configuration mode (Router(config-if)#)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists Cisco IOS modes as: 'User EXEC (>), Privileged EXEC (#), Global config, Interface config modes.' Global Configuration mode, entered from Privileged EXEC by typing 'configure terminal,' is where device-wide settings such as hostname, routing protocols, and VLANs are configured. User EXEC mode offers only limited monitoring commands. Privileged EXEC allows show and debug commands and is the gateway to configuration modes. Interface Configuration mode is used for settings specific to a single interface (e.g., IP address, duplex), not device-wide settings.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/fundamentals/configuration/xe-16/fundamentals-xe-16-book/cf-cli-basics.html","label":"Cisco – Using the Cisco IOS CLI"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco Learning Network – CCNA 200-301 Exam Topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Cisco IOS command mode allows an administrator to make global configuration changes that affect the entire router, such as setting the hostname?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In IPv6, which protocol replaces the functions of both ARP and ICMP Redirect that were used in IPv4?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DHCPv6"},{"id":"b","text":"Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP)"},{"id":"c","text":"SLAAC"},{"id":"d","text":"ICMPv4"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'NDP (replaces ARP+ICMP redirect): NS/NA, RS/RA.' Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP) uses Neighbor Solicitation (NS) and Neighbor Advertisement (NA) messages to perform the address resolution function that ARP handled in IPv4, and Router Solicitation (RS) / Router Advertisement (RA) messages to replace ICMP Redirect functionality. DHCPv6 provides stateful address assignment but does not replace ARP. SLAAC is a method for automatic address configuration using RA messages, but it is a function enabled by NDP, not a replacement for ARP itself. ICMPv4 is an IPv4 protocol and has no role in IPv6 neighbor resolution.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipv6_basic/configuration/xe-16/ip6b-xe-16-book/ip6-nd-overview.html","label":"Cisco – IPv6 Neighbor Discovery"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc4861","label":"RFC 4861 – Neighbor Discovery for IP version 6 (IPv6)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In IPv6, which protocol replaces the functions of both ARP and ICMP Redirect that were used in IPv4?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to carry traffic for VLANs 10, 20, and 30 across a link between two Cisco switches. Which port type and tagging standard should be configured on that link?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Access port using 802.1Q tagging"},{"id":"b","text":"Trunk port using 802.1Q tagging"},{"id":"c","text":"Trunk port using 802.3ad tagging"},{"id":"d","text":"Access port with no tagging required"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that trunk ports carry multiple VLANs using 802.1Q tagging, while access ports carry only a single VLAN and are untagged. 802.3ad is the standard for EtherChannel (LACP), not VLAN tagging. Since three VLANs must traverse a single link, a trunk port with 802.1Q tagging is the correct choice.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_vlan.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring VLANs and Trunking"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/17056-741-4.html","label":"IEEE 802.1Q VLAN Tagging Overview – Cisco"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to carry traffic for VLANs 10, 20, and 30 across a link between two Cisco switches. Which port type and tagging standard should be configured on that link?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which field in the 802.1Q frame header contains the 12-bit VLAN identifier?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"TPID (Tag Protocol Identifier)"},{"id":"b","text":"PCP (Priority Code Point)"},{"id":"c","text":"DEI (Drop Eligible Indicator)"},{"id":"d","text":"VID (VLAN Identifier) within the TCI"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, the 802.1Q tag is 4 bytes and consists of the TPID (set to 0x8100) and the TCI. Within the TCI, the 12-bit VID (VLAN Identifier) carries the actual VLAN number. PCP is a 3-bit quality-of-service field, and DEI is a single drop-eligibility bit — neither carries the VLAN ID.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/17056-741-4.html","label":"IEEE 802.1Q Standard – VLAN Tag Format"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which field in the 802.1Q frame header contains the 12-bit VLAN identifier?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security-conscious engineer wants to prevent a switch port connected to an end-user workstation from dynamically negotiating a trunk. Which command should be applied to that port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"switchport mode dynamic desirable"},{"id":"b","text":"switchport mode dynamic auto"},{"id":"c","text":"switchport mode access"},{"id":"d","text":"switchport mode trunk"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that for security, administrators should use 'switchport mode access' (or 'trunk') to disable DTP negotiation. DTP modes 'dynamic auto' and 'dynamic desirable' allow the port to negotiate a trunk, which is a security risk. Setting the port to static access mode disables DTP and fixes the port to carry only a single untagged VLAN.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/vtp/10558-21.html","label":"Cisco – Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_vlan.html","label":"Cisco Catalyst – Configuring Trunk Ports"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security-conscious engineer wants to prevent a switch port connected to an end-user workstation from dynamically negotiating a trunk. Which command should be applied to that port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator configures inter-VLAN routing on a single router interface connected to a Layer 2 switch. The router has subinterfaces each configured with 'encapsulation dot1q'. What is the name of this design?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Switch Virtual Interface (SVI)"},{"id":"b","text":"EtherChannel bundling"},{"id":"c","text":"Router-on-a-stick"},{"id":"d","text":"Layer 3 EtherChannel"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines router-on-a-stick as using subinterfaces on a single physical router interface, each with 'encapsulation dot1q' configured to tag traffic for a specific VLAN. This is distinct from an SVI, which is a virtual interface on a Layer 3 switch and is noted as better for scale. EtherChannel relates to link aggregation, not inter-VLAN routing.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_pi/configuration/xe-17/iri-xe-17-book/iri-intervlan-route.html","label":"Cisco – Inter-VLAN Routing Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator configures inter-VLAN routing on a single router interface connected to a Layer 2 switch. The router has subinterfaces each configured with 'encapsulation dot1q'. What is the name of this design?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Spanning Tree Protocol variant introduced the port states 'discarding', 'learning', and 'forwarding', replacing the five states used in 802.1D?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"802.1D STP"},{"id":"b","text":"802.1w RSTP"},{"id":"c","text":"802.1s MST"},{"id":"d","text":"802.3ad LACP"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists distinct port states for each STP variant. 802.1D STP uses five states: blocking, listening, learning, forwarding, and disabled. 802.1w RSTP reduces these to three: discarding, learning, and forwarding. 802.1s MST is a multi-instance variant built on top of RSTP. 802.3ad is unrelated — it is the LACP EtherChannel standard.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/24062-146.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1w)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Spanning Tree Protocol variant introduced the port states 'discarding', 'learning', and 'forwarding', replacing the five states used in 802.1D?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer wants switch ports connected to end devices to immediately begin forwarding traffic when a link comes up, bypassing the listening and learning states. Which STP feature should be enabled on those ports?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"BPDU Guard"},{"id":"b","text":"Root Guard"},{"id":"c","text":"PortFast"},{"id":"d","text":"Loop Guard"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that PortFast 'skips listening/learning' and should be applied on access ports connected to end devices. BPDU Guard is typically used in conjunction with PortFast to protect against BPDUs being received on those ports, but it does not by itself cause ports to skip STP states. Root Guard and Loop Guard are protective mechanisms for different STP threats.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/10588-74.html","label":"Cisco – PortFast, BPDU Guard, and Root Guard Configuration"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer wants switch ports connected to end devices to immediately begin forwarding traffic when a link comes up, bypassing the listening and learning states. Which STP feature should be enabled on those ports?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Cisco switch is configured with 'channel-group 1 mode active'. Which EtherChannel protocol is being used, and what mode on the neighboring switch would also form the bundle?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"PAgP; the neighbor must be set to desirable"},{"id":"b","text":"LACP; the neighbor can be set to active or passive"},{"id":"c","text":"LACP; the neighbor must also be set to active"},{"id":"d","text":"PAgP; the neighbor can be set to auto or desirable"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that LACP (IEEE 802.3ad, an open standard) uses 'active' and 'passive' modes. The keyword 'active' maps to LACP. A bundle forms when at least one side is 'active'; the other side can be 'active' or 'passive'. PAgP is Cisco proprietary and uses 'desirable' and 'auto' modes — not 'active'.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/int_hw/b_179_int_and_hw_9300_cg/configuring_etherchannel.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring EtherChannel"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/etherchannel/12023-4.html","label":"Cisco – EtherChannel Configuration Guide (LACP/PAgP)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Cisco switch is configured with 'channel-group 1 mode active'. Which EtherChannel protocol is being used, and what mode on the neighboring switch would also form the bundle?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless engineer is designing a 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi network for a large open-plan office and wants to deploy multiple access points without co-channel interference. Which set of channels should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Channels 1, 5, and 10"},{"id":"b","text":"Channels 1, 6, and 11"},{"id":"c","text":"Channels 2, 6, and 10"},{"id":"d","text":"Channels 3, 7, and 11"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that the non-overlapping channels in the 2.4 GHz US band are 1, 6, and 11. All other combinations listed include channels that overlap with at least one neighbor, which would cause co-channel or adjacent-channel interference. Using channels 1, 6, and 11 ensures each access point operates on a fully non-overlapping segment of the 2.4 GHz spectrum.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless/5500-series-wireless-controllers/116232-qanda-wlc-channel-00.html","label":"Cisco – Wireless LAN Channel Configuration Best Practices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
