  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A wireless engineer is designing a 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi network for a large open-plan office and wants to deploy multiple access points without co-channel interference. Which set of channels should be used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network technician is deploying Cisco lightweight access points in a branch office. Which protocol do these APs use to communicate with the Wireless LAN Controller (WLC)?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"LWAPP (Lightweight Access Point Protocol)"},{"id":"b","text":"CAPWAP (Control and Provisioning of Wireless Access Points)"},{"id":"c","text":"MPLS (Multiprotocol Label Switching)"},{"id":"d","text":"LLDP-MED (Link Layer Discovery Protocol – Media Endpoint Discovery)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Lightweight APs use CAPWAP tunnel to WLC (control + data).' CAPWAP is the current standard protocol that carries both control-plane and data-plane traffic between lightweight APs and the WLC. LWAPP was a predecessor that has been replaced by CAPWAP. MPLS is a WAN routing/switching technology, and LLDP-MED is used for voice VLAN discovery — neither is used for AP-to-WLC communication.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/controller/9800/17-12/config-guide/b_wl_17_12_cg/m_capwap_overview.html","label":"Cisco – CAPWAP Tunneling for Wireless LAN Controllers"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5415","label":"RFC 5415 – Control And Provisioning of Wireless Access Points (CAPWAP) Protocol Specification"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network technician is deploying Cisco lightweight access points in a branch office. Which protocol do these APs use to communicate with the Wireless LAN Controller (WLC)?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An IP phone is connected to a Cisco access switch port. The switch is configured with a voice VLAN. Which protocols can the switch use to signal the voice VLAN information to the IP phone?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"STP and RSTP"},{"id":"b","text":"LACP and PAgP"},{"id":"c","text":"CDP and LLDP-MED"},{"id":"d","text":"VTP and DTP"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that a voice VLAN provides 'separate L2 for IP phones via CDP/LLDP-MED.' Cisco Discovery Protocol (CDP) is the Cisco-proprietary mechanism, while LLDP-MED is the vendor-neutral standard for communicating voice VLAN information to IP phones. STP/RSTP manages the Layer 2 loop-free topology, LACP/PAgP are EtherChannel negotiation protocols, and VTP/DTP relate to VLAN propagation and trunk negotiation — none of these signal voice VLAN assignment to phones.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_voice_vlan.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Voice VLAN"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ios-nx-os-software/ios-xe-17/217434-configure-lldp-med-on-cisco-ios-xe.html","label":"Cisco – LLDP-MED and Voice VLAN"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An IP phone is connected to a Cisco access switch port. The switch is configured with a voice VLAN. Which protocols can the switch use to signal the voice VLAN information to the IP phone?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer configures a Cisco router to forward DHCP requests from clients on VLAN 10 to a DHCP server located on a different subnet. Which IOS command must be applied to the VLAN 10 interface to enable this relay functionality?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"ip helper-address <dhcp-server-ip>"},{"id":"b","text":"ip dhcp relay <dhcp-server-ip>"},{"id":"c","text":"ip dhcp-server <dhcp-server-ip>"},{"id":"d","text":"ip forward-protocol udp 67 <dhcp-server-ip>"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'ip helper-address for relaying DHCP across subnets.' When a DHCP Discover broadcast reaches a router interface, the ip helper-address command converts it to a unicast packet destined for the specified DHCP server, allowing DHCP to function across layer-3 boundaries. Option B ('ip dhcp relay') is not a valid IOS command. Option C ('ip dhcp-server') does not exist in this form. Option D references ip forward-protocol, which controls which UDP ports are forwarded, but the actual relay destination is still configured with ip helper-address — using ip forward-protocol alone is insufficient.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/dynamic-address-allocation-resolution/27470-100.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding and Troubleshooting DHCP in Catalyst Switch or Enterprise Networks"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipaddr_dhcp/configuration/xe-16/dhcp-xe-16-book/config-dhcp-server.html","label":"Cisco IOS IP Addressing Services Command Reference – ip helper-address"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer configures a Cisco router to forward DHCP requests from clients on VLAN 10 to a DHCP server located on a different subnet. Which IOS command must be applied to the VLAN 10 interface to enable this relay functionality?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company uses PAT (NAT overload) so that multiple inside hosts share a single public IP address for Internet access. A network administrator reviews the NAT translation table and sees the term 'inside global' used for an address. What does 'inside global' represent in Cisco NAT terminology?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The private IP address assigned to an inside host as seen from within the internal network"},{"id":"b","text":"The public IP address that represents an inside host as seen from the outside network"},{"id":"c","text":"The IP address of an outside destination host as seen from the inside network"},{"id":"d","text":"The IP address of an outside destination host as seen from the outside network"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly defines: 'Inside local (private inside), inside global (public inside), outside local, outside global.' Inside global is the public-facing IP address that represents an inside host as viewed from the outside (Internet). It is the address that appears as the source IP in packets after NAT/PAT translation. Option A describes the 'inside local' address (the private IP of the inside host). Option C describes the 'outside local' address. Option D describes the 'outside global' address.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/4606-8.html","label":"Cisco – NAT Order of Operations and Terminology"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/26704-nat-faq-00.html","label":"Cisco – How NAT Works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company uses PAT (NAT overload) so that multiple inside hosts share a single public IP address for Internet access. A network administrator reviews the NAT translation table and sees the term 'inside global' used for an address. What does 'inside global' represent in Cisco NAT terminology?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A VoIP administrator wants to guarantee low latency and jitter for voice traffic on a WAN link. According to QoS best practices covered in CCNA, which queuing mechanism is specifically recommended for voice traffic, and what DSCP value is typically assigned to it?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"CBWFQ with DSCP AF41 (34)"},{"id":"b","text":"LLQ with DSCP EF (46)"},{"id":"c","text":"WFQ with DSCP CS5 (40)"},{"id":"d","text":"PQ with DSCP AF11 (10)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Queueing: LLQ (Low Latency Queueing) for voice' and 'EF (Expedited Forwarding, DSCP 46) for voice.' LLQ provides a strict-priority queue that services voice packets before all other traffic, ensuring minimal latency and jitter. EF (DSCP 46) is the standardized Per-Hop Behavior marking for voice bearer traffic. Option A is incorrect because CBWFQ alone provides bandwidth guarantees but not a strict-priority queue; AF41 is used for video, not voice. Option C is incorrect; standard WFQ does not provide the deterministic low-latency treatment LLQ does, and CS5 is not the primary voice marking. Option D is incorrect; legacy PQ is not the modern recommended mechanism, and AF11 is used for low-priority data.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/qos_conmgt/configuration/xe-16/qos-conmgt-xe-16-book/qos-conmgt-oview.html","label":"Cisco – Low Latency Queueing (LLQ) for Voice"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3246","label":"RFC 3246 – An Expedited Forwarding PHB"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A VoIP administrator wants to guarantee low latency and jitter for voice traffic on a WAN link. According to QoS best practices covered in CCNA, which queuing mechanism is specifically recommended for voice traffic, and what DSCP value is typically assigned to it?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network operations team needs to receive asynchronous alerts from Cisco routers when specific events occur (such as interface failures), without the management station having to poll the devices. The team also requires that delivery of these notifications be acknowledged. Which SNMP operation meets both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"SNMP Get"},{"id":"b","text":"SNMP Trap"},{"id":"c","text":"SNMP Inform"},{"id":"d","text":"SNMP Get-Bulk"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'trap (notification), inform (acked notification).' Both traps and informs are asynchronous event-driven notifications sent from the agent to the manager without polling. However, only Inform messages require an acknowledgement from the manager; if no acknowledgement is received, the agent retransmits the inform. Traps (Option B) are fire-and-forget — no acknowledgement is sent by the manager, so delivery is not guaranteed. Option A (Get) and Option D (Get-Bulk) are polling operations initiated by the manager, not asynchronous alerts from the device.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/snmp/configuration/xe-16/snmp-xe-16-book/nm-snmp-cfg-snmp-support.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring SNMP Support"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3416","label":"RFC 3416 – Version 2 of the Protocol Operations for SNMP (InformRequest-PDU)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network operations team needs to receive asynchronous alerts from Cisco routers when specific events occur (such as interface failures), without the management station having to poll the devices. The team also requires that delivery of these notifications be acknowledged. Which SNMP operation meets both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Three routers are configured with HSRP on the same LAN segment. Router A is currently the active HSRP router. A network engineer wants Router B to automatically take over as the active router if a specific WAN uplink tracked by a track object degrades. Which HSRP feature enables this automatic role transition based on the state of a tracked object?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"HSRP preemption with object tracking"},{"id":"b","text":"GLBP active virtual forwarder election"},{"id":"c","text":"VRRP master/backup priority advertisement"},{"id":"d","text":"HSRP authentication with MD5"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'FHRP: HSRP (active/standby)' and 'Track objects for failover.' In HSRP, object tracking allows the router's HSRP priority to be automatically decremented when a tracked interface or object (such as a WAN uplink) goes down. Combined with HSRP preemption enabled on Router B, this allows Router B to win the active role when Router A's priority drops below Router B's. Without preemption, a router with a higher priority will not take over from the current active router. Option B describes GLBP, a different FHRP that provides load balancing rather than simple failover. Option C describes VRRP, not HSRP. Option D refers to HSRP MD5 authentication, which secures HSRP messages but does not provide failover based on tracked objects.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipapp_fhrp/configuration/xe-16/fhp-xe-16-book/fhp-hsrp-ip-tracking.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring HSRP Object Tracking"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/hot-standby-router-protocol-hsrp/9234-hsrpfaq.html","label":"Cisco – Hot Standby Router Protocol (HSRP) – FAQ"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Three routers are configured with HSRP on the same LAN segment. Router A is currently the active HSRP router. A network engineer wants Router B to automatically take over as the active router if a specific WAN uplink tracked by a track object degrades. Which HSRP feature enables this automatic role transition based on the state of a tracked object?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer wants to retrieve the current running configuration from a Cisco IOS-XE device using NETCONF. Which TCP port does NETCONF use by default, and over which transport protocol does it operate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Port 443 over TLS"},{"id":"b","text":"Port 830 over SSH"},{"id":"c","text":"Port 8080 over HTTP"},{"id":"d","text":"Port 22 over SSH"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, NETCONF (RFC 6241) operates using XML over SSH on port 830. Port 443 is used for HTTPS/TLS (associated with RESTCONF), port 22 is the default SSH port for interactive CLI sessions (not NETCONF), and port 8080 is a common alternative HTTP port unrelated to NETCONF. When a network engineer issues a NETCONF get-config request, the session is established on TCP port 830 using SSH as the mandatory transport.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc6241","label":"RFC 6241 – Network Configuration Protocol (NETCONF)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/prog/configuration/1612/b_1612_programmability_cg/configuring_yang_datamodel.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE NETCONF/YANG Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer wants to retrieve the current running configuration from a Cisco IOS-XE device using NETCONF. Which TCP port does NETCONF use by default, and over which transport protocol does it operate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which HTTP method should a developer use when calling the Cisco DNA Center (Catalyst Center) northbound REST API to create a new network site object that does not yet exist?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"GET"},{"id":"b","text":"PATCH"},{"id":"c","text":"POST"},{"id":"d","text":"PUT"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that in REST APIs, POST is used to create a new resource. GET is used for read operations, PATCH modifies an existing resource partially, and PUT replaces an existing resource entirely. Because the site object does not yet exist, POST is the correct method to create it. Using PUT on a non-existent resource would typically require the client to specify the full resource URI and may return an error if the resource is absent, whereas POST submits a new entity to the collection endpoint.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/dna-center/#!create-site","label":"Cisco DNA Center API Reference – Sites"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/learning/tracks/netprog-eng/network-programmability-foundation/rest-api-fundamentals/step/1","label":"Cisco DevNet: REST API Fundamentals"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which HTTP method should a developer use when calling the Cisco DNA Center (Catalyst Center) northbound REST API to create a new network site object that does not yet exist?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Python script uses the `requests` library to call a REST API endpoint on Cisco DNA Center. The API returns HTTP status code 401. What does this status code indicate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The request was successful and the resource was created."},{"id":"b","text":"The client is not authorized because valid credentials were not provided."},{"id":"c","text":"The server understood the request but refuses to authorize it due to insufficient permissions."},{"id":"d","text":"The requested resource was not found on the server."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists 401 Unauthorized under 4xx client error codes, indicating that the client has not provided valid authentication credentials. Option A describes a 201 Created response (2xx success). Option C describes a 403 Forbidden response, which means the server understood the identity of the caller but the caller lacks permission. Option D describes a 404 Not Found error. When a developer sees 401, they should check that the authentication token or credentials included in the request are correct and have not expired.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/401","label":"MDN Web Docs – HTTP 401 Unauthorized"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/dna-center/#!authentication","label":"Cisco DNA Center API Authentication Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
