  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Python script uses the `requests` library to call a REST API endpoint on Cisco DNA Center. The API returns HTTP status code 401. What does this status code indicate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer is comparing traditional network architectures with Software-Defined Networking (SDN). Which statement correctly describes a fundamental difference between the two approaches?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Traditional networks use a centralized control plane, while SDN uses a distributed control plane on each device."},{"id":"b","text":"Traditional networks have the control plane distributed across each device, while SDN centralizes the control plane in a controller."},{"id":"c","text":"SDN eliminates the data plane entirely by moving all packet forwarding to the controller."},{"id":"d","text":"Traditional networks rely solely on REST APIs for configuration management, while SDN uses CLI."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Traditional: distributed control plane (each device runs routing). SDN: centralized control plane (controller programs data plane).' Option A reverses these definitions. Option C is incorrect because SDN still relies on a data plane (forwarding hardware) on each device; only the control plane is centralized. Option D inverts reality — traditional networks depend on CLI and proprietary protocols, not REST APIs, while SDN introduces programmatic interfaces like REST.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/software-defined-networking/overview.html","label":"Cisco – Introduction to Software Defined Networking"},{"url":"https://www.ciscopress.com/store/ccna-200-301-official-cert-guide-library-9780135792735","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – SDN Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer is comparing traditional network architectures with Software-Defined Networking (SDN). Which statement correctly describes a fundamental difference between the two approaches?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network automation engineer needs to manage Cisco IOS devices using an agentless configuration management tool that uses YAML-based playbooks. Which tool best fits this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Puppet"},{"id":"b","text":"Chef"},{"id":"c","text":"Terraform"},{"id":"d","text":"Ansible"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Ansible: agentless, YAML playbooks, modules (ios_config, ios_facts).' This matches all three requirements in the question — agentless operation, YAML playbook syntax, and IOS device support via dedicated modules. Puppet and Chef are agent-based tools that require a software agent installed on managed nodes, which is typically not feasible on network devices. Terraform is a declarative infrastructure provisioning tool that uses its own HCL language and maintains a state file; it is not agentless in the same sense and is not primarily designed for IOS device configuration management.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/collections/cisco/ios/index.html","label":"Ansible Network Automation – Cisco IOS modules"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/network-automation/detail/ansible/","label":"Cisco DevNet – Network Automation with Ansible"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network automation engineer needs to manage Cisco IOS devices using an agentless configuration management tool that uses YAML-based playbooks. Which tool best fits this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which data serialization format is natively used by NETCONF for encoding configuration and operational data exchanged between a controller and a managed device?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"JSON"},{"id":"b","text":"YAML"},{"id":"c","text":"XML"},{"id":"d","text":"CSV"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that NETCONF uses 'XML over SSH,' and separately notes 'XML: tag-based, used in NETCONF.' JSON is described as lightweight and key-value based, used in REST APIs (and also supported by RESTCONF). YAML is indentation-sensitive and used in Ansible playbooks. CSV is a flat file format with no structured hierarchy and has no role in NETCONF communications. RESTCONF, the HTTP-based sibling protocol, extends NETCONF/YANG and supports both JSON and XML, but native NETCONF messaging is XML.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc6241#section-4","label":"RFC 6241 – NETCONF Data Encoding (XML)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/prog/configuration/1612/b_1612_programmability_cg/configuring_yang_datamodel.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE Programmability – NETCONF and XML"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which data serialization format is natively used by NETCONF for encoding configuration and operational data exchanged between a controller and a managed device?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A senior engineer explains that Cisco DNA Center implements Intent-Based Networking (IBN). What does this mean in the context of network automation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Network engineers manually program each device CLI command to reflect the desired business outcome."},{"id":"b","text":"Business intent is expressed at a high level and the system automatically translates it into device-level configuration."},{"id":"c","text":"The controller only collects telemetry data and does not modify device configurations."},{"id":"d","text":"Devices autonomously learn and apply routing policies using on-device machine learning without a controller."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines Intent-Based Networking as 'business intent translated to network config' within the Cisco DNA Center / Catalyst Center context. This means an administrator expresses a high-level policy (e.g., segment a group of users) and the controller translates that into the specific NETCONF/YANG or CLI commands pushed to each device. Option A describes traditional manual configuration management, which IBN is designed to replace. Option C describes a read-only telemetry or assurance function, not IBN automation. Option D describes a hypothetical on-device ML approach, not the controller-driven IBN model Cisco implements.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/cloud-systems-management/dna-center/index.html","label":"Cisco DNA Center – Intent-Based Networking Overview"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/dna-center/","label":"Cisco DevNet – DNA Center Intent API"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A senior engineer explains that Cisco DNA Center implements Intent-Based Networking (IBN). What does this mean in the context of network automation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer wants to implement on-device automation on a Cisco IOS router so that a syslog message matching a specific pattern automatically triggers a CLI script — without relying on an external controller or management server. Which Cisco IOS feature should they use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"NETCONF edit-config operation"},{"id":"b","text":"Cisco Embedded Event Manager (EEM)"},{"id":"c","text":"Ansible ios_config module"},{"id":"d","text":"gNMI model-driven telemetry subscription"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cisco EEM (Embedded Event Manager): on-device automation via applets and Tcl scripts.' EEM allows a router or switch to monitor events (such as syslog messages, interface state changes, or CLI patterns) and execute an action locally — no external controller is needed. NETCONF edit-config is used to push configuration changes from an external management system, not for event-triggered on-device automation. The Ansible ios_config module runs from an external Ansible control node and is not on-device. gNMI is a telemetry streaming protocol used to push operational data to an external collector, not to trigger local scripts in response to events.$patch$, $patch$Automation and Programmability$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/eem/configuration/xe-16/eem-xe-16-book/eem-overview.html","label":"Cisco IOS Embedded Event Manager (EEM) Configuration Guide"},{"url":"https://developer.cisco.com/docs/ios-xe/#!embedded-event-manager","label":"Cisco DevNet – EEM Scripting"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer wants to implement on-device automation on a Cisco IOS router so that a syslog message matching a specific pattern automatically triggers a CLI script — without relying on an external controller or management server. Which Cisco IOS feature should they use?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to filter traffic based on both source IP address and destination TCP port number. Which type of ACL should be configured, and in which numbered range is it valid?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Standard ACL, numbered 1–99 or 1300–1999"},{"id":"b","text":"Extended ACL, numbered 100–199 or 2000–2699"},{"id":"c","text":"Standard ACL, numbered 100–199"},{"id":"d","text":"Extended ACL, numbered 1–99 or 1300–1999"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Extended ACLs (100-199 or 2000-2699): match src/dst IP, protocol, ports.' Because the requirement includes filtering on destination TCP port, an extended ACL is required. Standard ACLs (1–99, 1300–1999) match source IP only and cannot inspect ports or protocols.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/sec_data_acl/configuration/xe-16/sec-data-acl-xe-16-book/sec-access-list-ov.html","label":"Cisco – ACL Configuration Guide (IOS XE)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to filter traffic based on both source IP address and destination TCP port number. Which type of ACL should be configured, and in which numbered range is it valid?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$According to best practices for ACL placement, where should an extended ACL be applied relative to the traffic source?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"As close to the destination as possible to preserve routing flexibility"},{"id":"b","text":"At the core layer only, regardless of traffic direction"},{"id":"c","text":"As close to the source as possible to stop unwanted traffic early"},{"id":"d","text":"On every interface in both inbound and outbound directions simultaneously"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Extended ACLs … apply closest to source.' This prevents unwanted traffic from traversing the network unnecessarily. Standard ACLs, which match only source IP, should be placed closest to the destination to avoid accidentally blocking traffic before it can reach legitimate paths.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/access-lists/26448-ACLsamples.html","label":"Cisco – Best Practices for ACL Placement"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$According to best practices for ACL placement, where should an extended ACL be applied relative to the traffic source?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch port is configured with port security. After a violation occurs, the port is still forwarding traffic from authorized MAC addresses but increments the violation counter and drops frames from unknown MACs. Which violation mode is active?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Shutdown"},{"id":"b","text":"Protect"},{"id":"c","text":"Restrict"},{"id":"d","text":"Dynamic"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists three port-security violation modes: shutdown, restrict, and protect. 'Restrict' drops frames from violating MAC addresses, increments the violation counter, and sends a syslog/SNMP notification — but keeps the port up and forwards authorized traffic. 'Protect' also drops unknown frames but does NOT increment the violation counter or send alerts. 'Shutdown' disables the port entirely (err-disabled).$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9200/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/sec/b_179_sec_9200_cg/configuring_port_security.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Port Security (Catalyst Switches)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch port is configured with port security. After a violation occurs, the port is still forwarding traffic from authorized MAC addresses but increments the violation counter and drops frames from unknown MACs. Which violation mode is active?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Layer 2 switch is configured with DHCP snooping. An attacker on an untrusted port attempts to respond to client DHCP Discover messages with a rogue DHCP offer. What will DHCP snooping do with the rogue offer?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Forward it normally because DHCP snooping only inspects client requests"},{"id":"b","text":"Drop it because DHCP server replies received on untrusted ports are discarded"},{"id":"c","text":"Rate-limit it and forward it after a configurable delay"},{"id":"d","text":"Forward it and log the source MAC in the snooping binding table as a trusted entry"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'DHCP snooping classifies ports as trusted (uplink) vs untrusted.' DHCP server messages (Offer, Ack) arriving on untrusted ports are dropped because legitimate DHCP servers should only be reachable through trusted uplink ports. This prevents rogue DHCP servers from poisoning clients with false gateway or DNS information.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9200/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/sec/b_179_sec_9200_cg/configuring_dhcp_snooping.html","label":"Cisco – DHCP Snooping Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Layer 2 switch is configured with DHCP snooping. An attacker on an untrusted port attempts to respond to client DHCP Discover messages with a rogue DHCP offer. What will DHCP snooping do with the rogue offer?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer is choosing between TACACS+ and RADIUS for a solution that requires per-command authorization on Cisco routers and full encryption of the authentication payload. Which protocol best meets both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"RADIUS, because it uses TCP and encrypts the entire payload"},{"id":"b","text":"TACACS+, because it uses TCP, encrypts the entire payload, and supports command authorization"},{"id":"c","text":"RADIUS, because it operates on port 49 and provides granular command authorization"},{"id":"d","text":"TACACS+, because it uses UDP for low-latency authorization checks"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'TACACS+ (port 49, TCP, encrypts entire payload, command authorization) vs RADIUS (port 1812/1813, UDP, encrypts only password).' TACACS+ satisfies both requirements: it uses TCP (reliable transport), encrypts the full packet body (not just the password), and uniquely supports separate authorization steps including per-command authorization. RADIUS encrypts only the password field and does not natively support per-command authorization.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/remote-authentication-dial-user-service-radius/13838-10.html","label":"Cisco – Comparing TACACS+ and RADIUS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer is choosing between TACACS+ and RADIUS for a solution that requires per-command authorization on Cisco routers and full encryption of the authentication payload. Which protocol best meets both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator runs the command 'service password-encryption' on a Cisco router. Which statement accurately describes the effect and limitation of this command?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"It applies MD5 hashing (Type 5) to all passwords, making them cryptographically irreversible"},{"id":"b","text":"It applies a weak, reversible obfuscation (Type 7) to plaintext passwords stored in the configuration"},{"id":"c","text":"It applies scrypt hashing (Type 9) to the enable password, providing strong one-way encryption"},{"id":"d","text":"It encrypts passwords using AES-128 and stores the key in NVRAM separately from the config"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: ''service password-encryption' (Type 7, reversible).' Type 7 encoding uses a simple Vigenère-based cipher that is easily reversed with freely available tools — it is obfuscation, not true encryption. For strong password protection the source recommends 'enable secret', which uses MD5 (Type 5) or scrypt (Type 9), both one-way hashing algorithms.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/ipsec-negotiation-ike-protocols/46413-ios-password-encrypt.html","label":"Cisco – Protecting Passwords in Cisco IOS Devices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator runs the command 'service password-encryption' on a Cisco router. Which statement accurately describes the effect and limitation of this command?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless network must authenticate corporate laptops using digital certificates stored on each device, with no shared passphrase. The network must also use 802.1X as the authentication framework. Which combination of wireless security standard and EAP method satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"WPA2-Personal with EAP-FAST, using a Protected Access Credential (PAC)"},{"id":"b","text":"WPA2-Enterprise with EAP-TLS, using mutual certificate-based authentication"},{"id":"c","text":"WPA3-Personal with SAE, replacing PSK with a certificate exchange"},{"id":"d","text":"WEP with PEAP, using a shared key for initial association"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: '802.1X with EAP-TLS/PEAP/EAP-FAST' and 'WPA2-Enterprise (802.1X).' EAP-TLS requires both the server and the client to present X.509 certificates, making it the only listed method that relies solely on certificates without a shared passphrase. WPA2-Enterprise pairs 802.1X with a RADIUS back-end. WPA2-Personal uses a PSK; WPA3-Personal uses SAE (not certificates); WEP is obsolete and insecure.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/technology/vwlan/wlan-security/b_WLAN-Security/b_WLAN-Security_chapter_01.html","label":"Cisco – Wireless LAN Security Overview (EAP Methods)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A wireless network must authenticate corporate laptops using digital certificates stored on each device, with no shared passphrase. The network must also use 802.1X as the authentication framework. Which combination of wireless security standard and EAP method satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A site-to-site IPsec VPN is configured between two branch routers. The security team requires that the original IP headers of packets be hidden from intermediate devices on the public Internet. Which IPsec mode achieves this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Transport mode, which encrypts only the payload and leaves the original IP header intact"},{"id":"b","text":"Tunnel mode, which encapsulates the entire original packet inside a new IP header"},{"id":"c","text":"GRE-only mode, which encrypts both the inner and outer IP headers with AES"},{"id":"d","text":"Transport mode, which replaces the original IP header with an encrypted substitute"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies 'Transport vs tunnel mode' as a VPN concept. In tunnel mode, the entire original IP packet (including its header) is encrypted and encapsulated within a new outer IP packet, so intermediate routers see only the tunnel endpoints' addresses — the original source and destination IPs are hidden. Transport mode encrypts only the upper-layer payload and leaves the original IP header exposed, making it unsuitable when header confidentiality is required. Site-to-site IPsec VPNs between gateways use tunnel mode.$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security-vpn/ipsec-negotiation-ike-protocols/215470-ipsec-tunnel-mode-versus-transport-mode.html","label":"Cisco – IPsec Tunnel vs Transport Mode Explained"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A site-to-site IPsec VPN is configured between two branch routers. The security team requires that the original IP headers of packets be hidden from intermediate devices on the public Internet. Which IPsec mode achieves this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) is enabled on a VLAN. Which underlying feature must already be operational on the switch to provide DAI with its validation data?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"IP Source Guard binding table populated by 802.1X authentication"},{"id":"b","text":"DHCP snooping binding table mapping IP addresses to MAC addresses and ports"},{"id":"c","text":"Port security sticky MAC address table"},{"id":"d","text":"A static ARP access list defined under global configuration mode"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'DAI validates ARP via DHCP snooping binding table.' DHCP snooping builds a binding table that records each client's IP address, MAC address, VLAN, and port after a successful DHCP exchange. DAI uses this table to verify that ARP packets contain legitimate IP-to-MAC mappings; ARP packets that contradict the binding table are dropped. Without DHCP snooping enabled and populating the binding table, DAI has no data source to validate against (static ARP ACLs can supplement but DHCP snooping is the primary requirement).$patch$, $patch$Security Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9200/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/sec/b_179_sec_9200_cg/configuring_dynamic_arp_inspection.html","label":"Cisco – Dynamic ARP Inspection Configuration Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI) is enabled on a VLAN. Which underlying feature must already be operational on the switch to provide DAI with its validation data?$patch$);

