         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"/48"},{"id":"b","text":"/56"},{"id":"c","text":"/64"},{"id":"d","text":"/128"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that /64 is used for LAN segments in IPv6. This is also required for SLAAC and EUI-64 host address generation, as the host portion is built from the 64-bit interface identifier derived from the MAC address. A /48 is typically assigned to a site, /56 to a customer block, and /128 is a host route (single address).$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipv6_basic/configuration/xe-16/ip6b-xe-16-book/ip6-add-basic-conn.html","label":"Cisco – IPv6 Addressing and Basic Connectivity"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
