INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Cisco IOS command mode is indicated by the prompt 'Switch#' and allows the administrator to view the device's full running configuration?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"User EXEC mode"},{"id":"b","text":"Global configuration mode"},{"id":"c","text":"Interface configuration mode"},{"id":"d","text":"Privileged EXEC mode"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies the '#' symbol as the prompt for Privileged EXEC mode (e.g., Switch#). This mode provides access to commands like 'show running-config', 'show version', and 'copy run start'. User EXEC mode uses the '>' prompt and has limited show commands. Global configuration mode uses '(config)#' and interface configuration mode uses '(config-if)#'. The 'show running-config' command is only available in Privileged EXEC mode.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/fundamentals/configuration/xe-16/fundamentals-xe-16-book/cf-cli-overview.html","label":"Cisco IOS XE – Understanding Command Modes"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Cisco IOS command mode is indicated by the prompt 'Switch#' and allows the administrator to view the device's full running configuration?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An IPv4 subnet is configured as 192.168.10.0/30. How many usable host addresses does this subnet provide?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"1"},{"id":"b","text":"2"},{"id":"c","text":"6"},{"id":"d","text":"14"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that a /30 subnet contains 4 total addresses (2² = 4), of which 2 are usable for hosts — one is the network address and one is the broadcast address. This makes /30 subnets ideal for point-to-point links between two devices such as a router-to-router WAN link. A /31 (RFC 3021) provides only 2 addresses with no broadcast, usable for point-to-point without broadcast. A /28 provides 14 usable hosts and /29 provides 6 usable hosts.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html","label":"Cisco – IP Addressing and Subnetting for New Users"},{"url":"https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3021","label":"RFC 3021 – Using 31-Bit Prefixes on IPv4 Point-to-Point Links"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An IPv4 subnet is configured as 192.168.10.0/30. How many usable host addresses does this subnet provide?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which IPv6 address type is automatically assigned to every IPv6-enabled interface and is only valid for communication on the local link segment?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Global Unicast Address (GUA)"},{"id":"b","text":"Unique Local Address (ULA)"},{"id":"c","text":"Link-Local Address (LLA)"},{"id":"d","text":"Anycast Address"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material identifies Link-Local Addresses as using the FE80::/10 prefix and being valid only on the local link segment. Every IPv6-enabled interface automatically generates a Link-Local address using EUI-64 or random generation. They are used by NDP (Neighbor Discovery Protocol) for functions such as Router Solicitation/Advertisement. Global Unicast Addresses (2000::/3) are routable on the Internet, and Unique Local Addresses (FC00::/7) are the IPv6 equivalent of RFC 1918 private addresses — both require explicit configuration or SLAAC/DHCPv6.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipv6_basic/configuration/xe-16/ip6b-xe-16-book/ip6-add-basic-conn.html#GUID-3B06D3B2-8E5C-47A5-B81C-2B4CE6E428DF","label":"Cisco – IPv6 Address Types"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which IPv6 address type is automatically assigned to every IPv6-enabled interface and is only valid for communication on the local link segment?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A technician is running a cable between two switches in the same wiring closet and notices that the switches are older models that do not support Auto-MDIX. Which cable type should the technician use to connect the two switches directly?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Straight-through copper Ethernet cable"},{"id":"b","text":"Crossover copper Ethernet cable"},{"id":"c","text":"Single-mode fiber cable"},{"id":"d","text":"Rollover (console) cable"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material notes that crossover cables are used to connect like devices (e.g., switch-to-switch or PC-to-PC) when Auto-MDIX is not available. Auto-MDIX automatically detects and adjusts for the required cable type, but on older devices without this feature, a crossover cable must be used manually. A straight-through cable is used to connect unlike devices (e.g., switch to router or switch to PC). Single-mode fiber is for long-distance links, and a rollover cable is used for out-of-band console management access.$patch$, $patch$Network Fundamentals$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/routers/7200-series-routers/12933-cat5.html","label":"Cisco – Ethernet Cabling Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A technician is running a cable between two switches in the same wiring closet and notices that the switches are older models that do not support Auto-MDIX. Which cable type should the technician use to connect the two switches directly?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator configures a switch port to carry traffic for multiple VLANs. Which IEEE standard defines the tagging mechanism used to identify VLAN membership on trunk links?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"802.1D"},{"id":"b","text":"802.1Q"},{"id":"c","text":"802.1w"},{"id":"d","text":"802.3ad"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$802.1Q is the IEEE standard that defines VLAN tagging on trunk links. As noted in the source material, the 802.1Q tag is 4 bytes consisting of a TPID of 0x8100 plus a TCI field containing PCP, DEI, and a 12-bit VLAN ID (VID). 802.1D defines classic STP, 802.1w defines RSTP, and 802.3ad defines LACP for EtherChannel — none of which are VLAN tagging standards.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/17056-741-4.html","label":"Cisco – 802.1Q VLAN Trunking Overview"},{"url":"https://standards.ieee.org/ieee/802.1Q/10323/","label":"IEEE 802.1Q Standard (overview)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator configures a switch port to carry traffic for multiple VLANs. Which IEEE standard defines the tagging mechanism used to identify VLAN membership on trunk links?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which two statements accurately describe the native VLAN on an 802.1Q trunk port? (Choose ONE correct answer as this is a SINGLE question.) A network engineer wants to improve trunk security. What should be done with the native VLAN?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Traffic on the native VLAN is always dropped by the far-end switch."},{"id":"b","text":"The native VLAN sends and receives untagged traffic across a trunk link, and VLAN 1 should be avoided as the native VLAN for security reasons."},{"id":"c","text":"The native VLAN must be VLAN 1 and cannot be changed per the 802.1Q standard."},{"id":"d","text":"Traffic on the native VLAN is double-tagged automatically by Cisco switches."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Per the source material, the native VLAN carries untagged traffic on a trunk and it is recommended to avoid VLAN 1 as the native VLAN for security purposes (VLAN hopping attacks exploit the default native VLAN). Option A is incorrect — native VLAN traffic is forwarded, not dropped. Option C is incorrect — although VLAN 1 is the default, it can and should be changed. Option D is incorrect — double-tagging is a potential attack vector, not an automatic switch behavior.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_vlans.html","label":"Cisco – VLAN Security Best Practices"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/8021q/17056-741-4.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding 802.1Q Tunneling and Native VLAN"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which two statements accurately describe the native VLAN on an 802.1Q trunk port? (Choose ONE correct answer as this is a SINGLE question.) A network engineer wants to improve trunk security. What should be done with the native VLAN?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A switch port connected to a PC should never negotiate a trunk link with the end device. Which command should the administrator apply to harden this access port against DTP-based trunk negotiation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"switchport mode dynamic desirable"},{"id":"b","text":"switchport mode dynamic auto"},{"id":"c","text":"switchport mode access"},{"id":"d","text":"switchport nonegotiate"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that for security, 'switchport mode access' or 'trunk' should be used to disable DTP negotiation on ports where it is not needed. 'switchport mode access' configures the port as a permanent access port and disables DTP negotiation entirely on that port. 'dynamic desirable' and 'dynamic auto' both leave DTP active and can negotiate trunk links, which is a security risk. 'switchport nonegotiate' stops DTP but is typically used with 'switchport mode trunk' — on an end-user port, explicitly setting 'mode access' is the recommended approach.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/tech/lan-switching/dynamic-trunking-protocol-dtp/index.html","label":"Cisco – Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/vtp/10558-21.html","label":"Cisco – Catalyst Switch Security: Disabling DTP"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A switch port connected to a PC should never negotiate a trunk link with the end device. Which command should the administrator apply to harden this access port against DTP-based trunk negotiation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator is implementing Rapid PVST+ on a Cisco Catalyst switch. Which port states are valid in RSTP (802.1w)?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Blocking, Listening, Learning, Forwarding"},{"id":"b","text":"Discarding, Learning, Forwarding"},{"id":"c","text":"Blocking, Learning, Forwarding, Disabled"},{"id":"d","text":"Listening, Learning, Forwarding, Standby"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material clearly distinguishes STP and RSTP port states: classic 802.1D STP uses Blocking, Listening, Learning, Forwarding, and Disabled; whereas RSTP (802.1w) consolidates these into three states: Discarding, Learning, and Forwarding. Option A lists classic STP states. Options C and D are incorrect or fabricated combinations. Cisco's Rapid PVST+ implements 802.1w on a per-VLAN basis using these three RSTP states.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/24062-146.html","label":"Cisco – Understanding Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1w)"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/lyr2/b_179_lyr2_9300_cg/configuring_stp.html","label":"Cisco – Spanning Tree Protocol Features"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator is implementing Rapid PVST+ on a Cisco Catalyst switch. Which port states are valid in RSTP (802.1w)?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An access layer switch has a workstation connected to Fa0/3. The network team wants to ensure the port immediately begins forwarding traffic when the workstation boots, bypassing the Listening and Learning STP states. Which STP feature should be configured on this port?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"BPDU Guard"},{"id":"b","text":"Root Guard"},{"id":"c","text":"PortFast"},{"id":"d","text":"Loop Guard"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that PortFast 'skips listening/learning' and should be applied on access ports (ports connected to end devices, not to other switches). This allows the port to transition directly from Blocking to Forwarding, reducing connection delay for end devices. BPDU Guard is often used alongside PortFast to err-disable the port if a BPDU is received (protecting against rogue switches) but does not itself skip STP states. Root Guard prevents a port from becoming a root port. Loop Guard protects against unidirectional link failures. Neither Root Guard, Loop Guard, nor BPDU Guard cause the port to bypass the Listening/Learning states.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/lyr2/b_179_lyr2_9300_cg/configuring_optional_spanning_tree_features.html","label":"Cisco – PortFast, BPDU Guard, and BPDU Filter"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/spanning-tree-protocol/10553-3.html","label":"Cisco – Using PortFast and Other Commands to Fix Workstation Startup Connectivity Delays"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An access layer switch has a workstation connected to Fa0/3. The network team wants to ensure the port immediately begins forwarding traffic when the workstation boots, bypassing the Listening and Learning STP states. Which STP feature should be configured on this port?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is bundling four physical Gigabit Ethernet links between two Cisco switches using an open-standard protocol that allows negotiation of the EtherChannel. Which protocol should be used?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"PAgP in desirable mode"},{"id":"b","text":"LACP in active mode"},{"id":"c","text":"DTP in dynamic desirable mode"},{"id":"d","text":"VTP in server mode"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that LACP (Link Aggregation Control Protocol) is an open standard defined in IEEE 802.3ad, while PAgP (Port Aggregation Protocol) is Cisco proprietary. Since the requirement specifies an open-standard protocol, LACP is the correct choice. LACP uses active/passive modes for negotiation; 'active' actively initiates negotiation. DTP is for trunk negotiation, not link aggregation. VTP is a VLAN management protocol, not relevant to EtherChannel negotiation.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/etherchannel/12023-4.html","label":"Cisco – EtherChannel Configuration and Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/lyr2/b_179_lyr2_9300_cg/configuring_etherchannel.html","label":"Cisco – LACP Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network engineer is bundling four physical Gigabit Ethernet links between two Cisco switches using an open-standard protocol that allows negotiation of the EtherChannel. Which protocol should be used?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company deploys IP phones and PCs connected to the same switch ports. The switch must place voice traffic into a dedicated VLAN for quality of service. Which feature enables the switch to automatically detect and configure a separate VLAN for the IP phone traffic?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"VTP pruning"},{"id":"b","text":"Voice VLAN configured via CDP or LLDP-MED"},{"id":"c","text":"Router-on-a-stick with subinterfaces"},{"id":"d","text":"SVI configured on the L3 switch"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material specifically states that a Voice VLAN provides a 'separate L2 for IP phones via CDP/LLDP-MED.' When a voice VLAN is configured on a Cisco switch port, CDP or LLDP-MED is used to signal the voice VLAN ID to the IP phone, which then tags its voice traffic accordingly. VTP pruning controls which VLANs are active on trunk links, not voice segmentation. Router-on-a-stick and SVIs are inter-VLAN routing solutions, not mechanisms for assigning voice VLANs to switch ports.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_voice_vlan.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Voice VLAN"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/nwmgmt/b_179_nwmgmt_9300_cg/configuring_lldp.html","label":"Cisco – LLDP-MED and Voice VLAN"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company deploys IP phones and PCs connected to the same switch ports. The switch must place voice traffic into a dedicated VLAN for quality of service. Which feature enables the switch to automatically detect and configure a separate VLAN for the IP phone traffic?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A lightweight access point (AP) is being deployed in a branch office. The AP must forward all client data traffic through a centralized Wireless LAN Controller (WLC) for policy enforcement. Which tunneling protocol carries both control and data traffic between the lightweight AP and the WLC?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"GRE (Generic Routing Encapsulation)"},{"id":"b","text":"CAPWAP (Control and Provisioning of Wireless Access Points)"},{"id":"c","text":"IPsec tunnel mode"},{"id":"d","text":"MPLS Label Distribution Protocol (LDP)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that 'Lightweight APs use CAPWAP tunnel to WLC (control + data).' CAPWAP (Control and Provisioning of Wireless Access Points) is the standard tunneling protocol used between lightweight APs and a WLC, carrying both the control plane (management, configuration) and data plane (client traffic) in separate UDP channels. GRE, IPsec, and MPLS LDP are general-purpose or WAN protocols not used for the AP-to-WLC relationship in Cisco's wireless architecture.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/controller/9800/config-guide/b_wl_16_10_cg/capwap.html","label":"Cisco – CAPWAP Overview"},{"url":"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5415","label":"RFC 5415 – CAPWAP Protocol Specification"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
