INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A wireless network administrator is designing a 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi deployment for an open office floor. To minimize co-channel interference between adjacent access points, which set of non-overlapping channels should be used in the United States?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Channels 1, 5, 10"},{"id":"b","text":"Channels 1, 6, 11"},{"id":"c","text":"Channels 2, 6, 10"},{"id":"d","text":"Channels 3, 7, 11"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states 'non-overlapping 1, 6, 11 in 2.4 GHz US.' In the United States, the 2.4 GHz band is divided into 11 channels spaced 5 MHz apart, but each channel is 22 MHz wide. Only channels 1, 6, and 11 are spaced far enough apart (25 MHz) to avoid overlapping with each other, making them the only three non-overlapping channels. The other combinations listed all include channels that spectrally overlap with at least one other channel in the set, causing adjacent-channel interference.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless/5500-series-wireless-controllers/116661-technote-channel-00.html","label":"Cisco – Wireless LAN Channel Deployment"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/controller/9800/config-guide/b_wl_16_10_cg/radio-frequency.html","label":"Cisco – RF Fundamentals for CCNA Wireless"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
