INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to implement inter-VLAN routing on a single router connected to a Layer 2 switch via one physical link. The router must route traffic between VLAN 10 and VLAN 20. Which configuration approach should be used on the router interface?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a separate physical interface for each VLAN and assign IP addresses."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure subinterfaces on the physical interface, each with 'encapsulation dot1q' and the respective VLAN ID."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure a Switch Virtual Interface (SVI) on the router for each VLAN."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable IP routing globally and assign all VLANs to the same interface IP subnet."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines the router-on-a-stick approach as using 'subinterfaces with encapsulation dot1q.' When only a single physical link connects a router to a Layer 2 switch (carrying a trunk), the router is configured with logical subinterfaces (e.g., G0/0.10 and G0/0.20), each with an 'encapsulation dot1q <vlan-id>' command and a unique IP address for that VLAN's subnet. Option A requires multiple physical links, which contradicts the single-link constraint. SVIs (Option C) are configured on Layer 3 switches, not routers. Option D is technically invalid as placing all VLANs on one subnet defeats VLAN segmentation.$patch$, $patch$Network Access$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst9300/software/release/17-9/configuration_guide/vlan/b_179_vlan_9300_cg/configuring_intervlan_routing.html","label":"Cisco – Configuring Router on a Stick Inter-VLAN Routing"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/lan-switching/inter-vlan-routing/14976-50.html","label":"Cisco – Inter-VLAN Routing Operation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to implement inter-VLAN routing on a single router connected to a Layer 2 switch via one physical link. The router must route traffic between VLAN 10 and VLAN 20. Which configuration approach should be used on the router interface?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network administrator needs to allow DHCP clients on the 192.168.10.0/24 subnet to obtain addresses from a DHCP server located on a different subnet. Which IOS command must be configured on the router interface facing the client subnet to enable this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"ip dhcp pool CLIENT"},{"id":"b","text":"ip helper-address <dhcp-server-ip>"},{"id":"c","text":"ip dhcp relay enable"},{"id":"d","text":"service dhcp-proxy <dhcp-server-ip>"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'ip helper-address for relaying DHCP across subnets.' When a router receives a DHCP Discover broadcast from a client, the ip helper-address command configured on the incoming interface converts that broadcast into a unicast packet directed at the specified DHCP server IP, enabling cross-subnet DHCP relay. Option (a) defines a local DHCP pool on the router, which does not relay to an external server. Options (c) and (d) are not valid IOS commands.$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipaddr_dhcp/configuration/xe-16/dhcp-xe-16-book/config-dhcp-server.html","label":"Cisco IOS IP Addressing Services Configuration Guide – DHCP"},{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/training-events/training-certifications/exams/current-list/ccna-200-301.html","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide – DHCP Relay"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = '200-301-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A network administrator needs to allow DHCP clients on the 192.168.10.0/24 subnet to obtain addresses from a DHCP server located on a different subnet. Which IOS command must be configured on the router interface facing the client subnet to enable this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A network engineer is reviewing NAT translations on a Cisco router. Which NAT address type describes the routable (public) IP address that represents an inside host as seen from the outside network?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Inside local"},{"id":"b","text":"Outside local"},{"id":"c","text":"Inside global"},{"id":"d","text":"Outside global"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines: 'Inside local (private inside), inside global (public inside), outside local, outside global.' The inside global address is the public-facing (routable) IP that represents an inside private host as seen by devices on the outside network. Inside local is the private IP assigned to the host itself. Outside global is the real IP of the destination server on the Internet. Outside local is how that external destination appears from the inside (often the same as outside global unless destination NAT is in use).$patch$, $patch$IP Services$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/4606-8.html","label":"Cisco – NAT: Local and Global Definitions"},{"url":"https://learningnetwork.cisco.com/s/ccna-exam-topics","label":"Cisco CCNA 200-301 Exam Topics – IP Services"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
